Task 1: Introduction
While Python is traditionally executed directly as a standalone backend application, JavaScript was born to run on the client side — specifically embedded inside web browsers to make static documents interactive. However, the modern development landscape shifted dramatically with the release of Node.js, a runtime environment that extracts JavaScript from the browser sandbox, allowing it to run directly on server operating systems and command-line interfaces.
To highlight how language syntax shapes design, we will mirror our previous room’s project by building a “Guess the Number” game.
The structural goals remain unchanged:

• The engine generates a hidden integer between 1 and 20.

• The user inputs continuous guesses via terminal console prompts.

• The program evaluates boundaries and values to output tracking hints.
Task 2: Variables
Unlike Python, which instantiates variables instantly upon text assignment, JavaScript requires explicit initialization keywords to declare how a memory container should behave.

• let (Mutable Variables): Declares a standard pointer whose internal data value can change throughout the execution lifespan. We use this to track shifting parameters like user guesses and total attempts.

• const (Immutable Constants): Declares a hardlocked reference that cannot be reassigned or altered once defined. We use this to protect the randomly generated secret key.
let tries = 0;
let guess = 0;To generate our hidden target value dynamically between 1 and 20, we chain together JavaScript’s built-in mathematical methods:
const secret = Math.floor(Math.random() * 20) + 1;
• Math.random(): Natively supplies a floating-point decimal value between 0 (inclusive) and 1 (exclusive).

• 20: Stretches the mathematical boundary scale out to a decimal range between 0 and 19.999.

• Math.floor(): Truncates the decimal tail entirely, rounding down to the nearest whole integer (0 to 19).

• + 1: Shifts the complete spectrum index upward, establishing our precise target boundary of 1 to 20.
To push status notifications out to the user’s display console, we call the standardized system output method: console.log().
