Because JavaScript and Node.js were designed from the ground up to handle high-concurrency web servers, their engines are built around an asynchronous asynchronous framework meaning they are optimized not to halt or block execution threads while waiting for slow operations like text input.
Forcing Node.js to act like a traditional command-line program and freeze execution until a user presses Enter requires implementing explicit input/output interface streams using the readline/promises library hooks:
const text = await rl.question(“Take a guess: “);
guess = parseInt(text, 10);Asynchronous Mechanics Breakdown

• The await Modifier: Instructs the runtime engine to neatly pause processing right at that specific line until the user provides a terminal response.

• Explicit Type Parsing (parseInt): Like Python’s int(), this converts our incoming text string into a mathematical number block. The second argument (10) is the radix, which explicitly forces the engine to parse the input using standard base-10 decimal formatting.

• The try / finally Safe Block: Establishes a protective boundary around our execution loops. The system attempts to run everything inside the try frame, and ensures that no matter what errors occur, it safely transitions into the finally block to run rl.close() gracefully shutting down our open input streams to prevent persistent memory leaks.
