That number is out of range. Try again.Task 5: Iterations
To grant the player continuous attempts until they guess correctly, we wrap our input capture and conditional logic inside a standard while loop.
In JavaScript, the comparative operator for absolute inequality (“not equal to”) is written as !==. This strict inequality operator ensures that both the data value and the data type match up perfectly before breaking the loop structure.
Here is our finalized, complete game program architecture (guess_v3.js):

import * as readline from “node:readline/promises”;
import { stdin as input, stdout as output } from “node:process”;
const rl = readline.createInterface({ input, output });try {
const secret = Math.floor(Math.random() * 20) + 1;
let tries = 0;
let guess = 0;
console.log("I'm thinking of a number between 1 and 20");
// Repeat until the user guesses the secret number.
while (guess !== secret) {
const text = await rl.question("Take a guess: ");
guess = parseInt(text, 10);
tries = tries + 1;
// Give a hint using if / else if / else.
if (guess < 1 || guess > 20) {
console.log("That number is out of range. Try again.");
} else if (guess < secret) {
console.log("Too low, try again.");
} else if (guess > secret) {
console.log("Too high, try again.");
} else {
console.log("You got it in", tries, "tries!");
}
}
} finally {
rl.close();
}
Unlike Python, where indentation controls code block boundaries, JavaScript ignores spaces and uses explicit curly braces {} to define what code sits inside or outside the loop.
